Data analysis of EAC data¶

We look into the 3 year data provided by EAC conserning the load consumption/generation.

The total load can be estimated by: $$Load=TOTAL~Conventional + PV + WIND$$

Initialise and read data¶

In [1]:
from datetime import timedelta
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import cufflinks as cf
import plotly.offline
cf.go_offline()
cf.set_config_file(offline=False, world_readable=True)
In [2]:
exc_file19 = 'Export_production_2019.xlsx'
exc_file20 = 'Export_production_2020.xlsx'
cols = 'A,C,D,F'
In [3]:
df19 = pd.read_excel(exc_file19, usecols = cols, skiprows = 1,  index_col = 0, header = 0, verbose=True, parse_dates=True)
df20 = pd.read_excel(exc_file20, usecols = cols, skiprows = 1,  index_col = 0, header = 0, verbose=True, parse_dates=True)

tmp20 = pd.read_excel(exc_file, usecols = cols, sheet_name = '2020', skiprows = 0,  index_col = 0, header = 0, verbose=True, parse_dates=True)

Look into each year¶

We plot the data of each year individually.

In [10]:
df19.iplot(kind='lines',xTitle='Dates',yTitle='MW',title='2019')
In [11]:
df20.iplot(kind='lines',xTitle='Dates',yTitle='MW',title='2020')

Comparison¶

We first shift the three timeseries to make sure they all coincide with the weekdays.

In [12]:
df19["X_DATE"] = pd.to_datetime(df19.index + timedelta(days=365-1))
df19.set_index('X_DATE', inplace=True)
df20["X_DATE"] = pd.to_datetime(df20.index)
df20.set_index('X_DATE', inplace=True)

We create a joint table with the overlaping LOAD data.

In [13]:
alldf = df19[['LOAD19','TEMP19']]
alldf = alldf.merge(df20[['LOAD20','TEMP20']], left_index=True, right_index=True)

alldfWmean.iplot(kind='lines',y=['LOAD19','LOAD20'],xTitle='Dates',yTitle='MW',title='Weekly average only with work hours and work days')
